I cant tell from the video what is going on with the SMD resistors on the back of the tft.Can you take a close up of the back of the tft to verify that.Resistors R3 R4 and R5 on the back of the tft close to the SD card are shorted because they need to be bypassed because they will prevent data transfer from the SD card.it looks like R1 has also been shorted and that is not correct? but I cant be sure from the video.
SMD resistors R3,R4 and R5 on the back of the tft are 10K resistors that protect the SD card from the 5v arduino input.However, they slow down the data transfer rate from the Sd card to 1mhz.If you short out these resistors and use a voltage divider (which is on the custom board) then you can get 8mhz data transfer from the SD card.
here is a more detailed explanation
https://next-hack.com/index.php/2017/07/09/how-to-play-a-20-fps-video-on-arduino-26-enabling-high-speed-sd-transfers-on-a-1-8-tftsd-module/
I have used 2 different kinds of SD card with my board and they both work.
here is a link to one of them
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07P1XMKGJ/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_asin_title_o04_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1
As long as you dont use an HC card the program should work with any regular SD card.There may be different frame rates with different cards, but they should still work.

here is the response from the next hack team regarding pin 1
Dear Carl,
we think they  are referring to a 3.3V to 5V translator.
The pin 1 is actually an input for the Arduino, so you do not need a resistor divider, like the other signals (Which are Arduino Outputs, therefore they are driven at 5V, that would damage the SD/Display).
It *might be* better putting a 3.3V to 5V translator, to convert the 3.3V signal coming out the MISO of the SD, to 5V.
This would improve the noise margin. In fact from the ATMEGA328âs datasheet, the recommended high level voltage is 0.6 * VCC, i.e. 3V (while the SD card at most outputs 3.3V, i.e. very close).
However, if you look at the datasheet of ATMEGA328 (as we discussed in the article), a much lower voltage is required to make the ATMEGA328 believe itâs a logic one (2.5V. i.e. any voltage from 2.5V to 5V is read as 1).
From our article we wrote in fact:

âDuring SD to CPU or SD to DISPLAY
Here the problem is that the SD output is loaded by the 680 Ohm resistor. Furthermore, the SD is powered at 3.3V while the ATMEGA328 is powered at 5V. Luckily, when reading from the SD card, the CPU MOSI is high, and this, due to the divider induced by R11 and R12, has no effect to the high-level output voltage, which will be 3.3V, i.e. 0.3 V more than the worst case condition. (still in the ATMEGA328P datasheet the typical voltage above which the pin is detected as high is 2.5V). Problems might arise when the SD output is low, however, the maximum VIL is 1.5V when the ATMEGA328 is powered at 5V. Furthermore, the datasheet s hows tha t t he p in i s detecte d as low if its voltage is b elow 2V.â
Of course this is just an hack (and it works with the display we used), one would not use it in a commercially produced device!
Best Regards
Next-hack crew
